04258nam a22005055i 9780773588608DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735886087 a10.1515/97807735886082doi  a(DE-B1597)656442  a(OCoLC)1037934646  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR9199.2.L3 ǂb Z55 2013eb 7aLIT0140002bisacsh04a811.41 aBall, Eric, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aArchibald Lampman :bMemory, Nature, Progress /cEric Ball. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (408 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tAlchemy in the Imagination -- tThe Workings of Memory -- tWinter and Memory -- tThe Full Furnace -- tBeauty in Nature: Theory and Poetic Practice -- tDiscovering the Wilderness -- tHeat and Cold: An Inclusive Vision -- tLyrics of Earth: Genesis, Design, Meaning -- tLater Nature Poems -- tThrough Lapse and Strife -- tIdeas of Progress -- tPoems of Progress -- tHeroic Visionaries of Future Progress -- tIndex of Poems in The Poems of Archibald Lampman (including At the Long Sault) -- tTable of Contents of ȜAfoot with the Yearȝ and Lyrics of Earth -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTreasuring the past, savouring the present, and wanting to do right by the future, Archibald Lampman was a poet keenly focused on the workings of time. He was also a thinker of mystical predisposition. His goal was not to transcend time, but to find redemptive meaning within it. Archibald Lampman: Memory, Nature, Progress explores the ways in which Lampman pursued this goal in relation to the three faces of time. Memory fascinated Lampman. He relished the “alchemy” by which the dross of past experience could be left behind and the gold preserved. Nature compelled his mind and emotions, and his clear-eyed observations of both countryside and wilderness settings gave rise to a self-evolved poetics of inclusiveness. In his celebrations of nature in all its manifestations, mild or bleak, he anticipated the work of iconic Canadian painter Tom Thomson and he forecasted the environmentalism of our own time. Progress for Lampman spelled societal rectification. By forwarding the cause of social betterment, one was part of a movement larger than oneself, and this expansion, too, was redemptive. Archibald Lampman: Memory, Nature, Progress is the first book on this foundational figure in Canadian literature to appear in over twenty-five years and the first thematically focused study. Combining close analysis with biographical context, it shows how Lampman’s oeuvre was shaped by his responses to his physical surroundings and to his social-intellectual milieu, as filtered through his stubbornly independent outlook.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358860840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773588608423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773588608/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles